[Illinois may be found on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at http://healthmap.org/r/3KfP.

All officials at the track are desperately hoping this horse does not have the disease that could reinstate the quarantine. Horse owners are also hoping for a positive outcome.

This is a very nasty and often fatal disease in horses. Usually the disease is abbreviated as EHV for equine herpes virus or EHM for equine herpesvirus myeloencephalopathy.

Equine herpesvirus (EHV-1) infection in horses can cause respiratory and neurological disease, abortion in mares, and neonatal foal death. The neurological form of the disease is known as equine herpes myeloencephalopathy (EHM) and has the potential to cause high morbidity and mortality.

EHV-1 is easily spread and typically has an incubation period between 2-10 days. Respiratory shedding of the virus generally occurs for 7-10 days but may persist longer in infected horses. For this reason, the isolation period recommendation for confirmed positive EHM cases is 21 days. Clinical signs of EHM in horses may include nasal discharge, incoordination, hindquarter weakness, recumbency, lethargy, urine dribbling, and diminished tail tone. The prognosis for EHM positive horses depends on the severity of signs and the period of recumbency. Employing supportive treatment with intravenous fluids, anti-inflammatory drugs, anti-viral drugs, and other supportive measures may be beneficial, since there is no specific treatment for EHM.

Currently, no EHV-1 equine vaccine has a label claim for protection against the neurological strain of the virus.

The following resources are offered as a means of education regarding this disease:
1. EHV-1 Overview (University of California, Davis, School of Veterinary Medicine) http://www.vetmed.ucdavis.edu/ceh/ehv1_general.cfm
2. Frequently Asked Questions about EHV/EHM for Horse Owners - PDF (American Association of Equine Practitioners) http://www.aaep.org/images/files/FAQforEquineHerpesvirus(final)051911.pdf
3. EHV/EHM Brochure for Horse Owners (USDA-APHIS) http://www.aphis.usda.gov/vs/nahss/equine/ehv/equine_herpesvirus_brochure_2009.pdf
4. EHV-1 Webinar for Horse Owners -- presented by Drs Paul Lunn and Paul Morley on 24 May 2011 ("Equine Herpesvirus-1 (EHV-1): What Horse Owners Should Know"). http://www.thehorse.com/Videos/Webinars.aspx
5. USDA Equine Biosecurity Brochure (available in Spanish as well through USDA/APHIS) http://www.aphis.usda.gov/publications/animal_health/content/printable_version/HorseBioSecurity_final.pdf
6. AAEP EHV Control Guidelines. http://www.aaep.org/images/files/EquineHerpesvirusGuidelines051711.pdf

